What the final run produced
- The third CI run failed with a single compilation error:

  /src/main/java/com/java_template/application/processor/FetchInventoryProcessor.java:79: error: incompatible types: JsonNode cannot be converted to Map<String,Object>
      Map<String, Object> filters = job.getFilters();

- In words: some code (the FetchInventoryProcessor source that the compiler saw) still has an assignment expecting Map<String, Object> while job.getFilters() is (or the compiler thinks it is) a JsonNode. This is a type mismatch.

Why that error remains
- The codebase contained multiple places handling job.getFilters(). Historically the filters field was a Map<String,Object>; I updated the entity and many processors to use JsonNode, but the CI output shows the compiler saw an old assignment in FetchInventoryProcessor (or another place with the same code). The root cause is a remaining place in source that expects Map<String,Object> — this needs to be made robust to accept either JsonNode or Map (or be updated to use JsonNode consistently).

Recommended fix (how to resolve the remaining error)
- Make FetchInventoryProcessor (and any other remaining consumers) tolerant to both the old Map type and the new JsonNode type. Replace direct Map assignment with an Object and then normalize to a JsonNode for processing.

Suggested code change (patch snippet) — replace the blocking line(s) with the following pattern:

    // allow for either Map<String,Object> (legacy) or JsonNode (preferred)
    Object filtersObj = job.getFilters();
    com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode filtersNode = null;
    java.util.Map<String, Object> filtersMap = null;

    if (filtersObj instanceof com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode) {
        filtersNode = (com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode) filtersObj;
    } else if (filtersObj instanceof java.util.Map) {
        //noinspection unchecked
        filtersMap = (java.util.Map<String, Object>) filtersObj;
        filtersNode = objectMapper.valueToTree(filtersMap);
    }

    // then use filtersNode (check filtersNode != null and filtersNode.has("category") etc)
    if (filtersNode != null && filtersNode.has("category")) {
        condition = SearchConditionRequest.group("AND",
            Condition.of("$.category", "EQUALS", filtersNode.get("category").asText())
        );
    }

- Also update fetchFromExternalApi signature (if needed) to accept a JsonNode or Object and handle both types similarly.

Why this approach
- It is the most non-invasive and backward-compatible approach: repositories/clients that still send Map-based filters will continue to work, and new JsonNode-based filters are supported. After making this change the single remaining type mismatch should disappear.

